Five years ago, charity: water started with a birthday party. Everyone who came donated $20 and we raised $15,000. We sent that money to Africa and built our first wells in Uganda. This year, we're going back to the beginning, and you're invited. SOLD OUT BY 10 PM! Cello Joe (CD Release) with Justin Ancheta, Jason McGuire & Friends - $7/$10
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
Awaken Cafe & Oaktown Indie Mayhem present... Local musical vagabond cellojoe commands attention from start to finish as he offers up not just a set, but rather a full on performance featuring layered beatboxing, live looping, and a bit of emcee magic overtop his funky cello. Don't miss out on your chance to enjoy tracks from his new album "So Much Love" up close and personal. Mark your calendar for this one. Justin Ancheta (http://www.justinancheta.com/) is able to flawlessly harness elements of jazz, reggae, hip hop, and a dash of balkan influence to create his own style of world folk. Upbeat and inspiring in his lyricism with a top notch band at his side, these guys are unstoppable. Now add Jason McGuire (http://www.youtube.com/user/JasonMcGuireFlamenco), a flamenco extraordinaire, to the mix, and we have ourselves a party. Doors at 8pm Show at 9pm direct ticket link https://squareup.com/market/awaken-cafe/cello-joe-cd-release-with-justin-ancheta-jason-mcguire-friends $7 presale, $10 at the door.

Journey to the End of the Night: San Francisco 2013
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
IMPORTANT: This game will have a maximum attendance of 3,000. Online pre-registration is required, but it does not guarantee entry. Entry will be first-come, first-served, and anyone without a printed and signed waiver will not be able to participate. (If you have not yet registered online and received your waiver, use the link below.) We will start handing out materials by 6pm at Everett Middle School, and the game begins at 7pm, so arrive early to guarantee your participation! ONLINE PRE-REGISTRATION IS REQUIRED THIS YEAR AT: http://sfjourney.herokuapp.com/ The seventh edition of Journey to the End of the Night returns to the shadowy cityscape of San Francisco as part of the Come Out and Play festival. Last year, 2,000 participants helped take over city streets in the name of play, and this year players will once more dash down hidden alleys, encounter mysterious strangers, and change how they experience the city. Journey to the End of the Night is a free street game played across cities around the world, spreading from San Francisco to Chicago, Washington, DC, Milan, Berlin, Mexico City, Christchurch, and beyond. Players sporting colored ribbons will race through a series of nonlinear checkpoints scattered throughout the city, while avoiding being caught by chasers. Those who survive will be praised and feted at the end party. Those who fall will become chasers themselves, rising in undeath to pursue the remaining runners. This year, there will be two colors of runners, each competing to get as many of their color as possible to the end point. For one night, drop your relations, your work and leisure activities, and all your usual motives for movement and action, and let yourself be drawn by the attractions of the chase and the encounters you find there. No bicycles, no skates, no cars, no taxis. You may only travel on foot or by public transportation. Wear comfortable shoes, and bring water. Prizes will be awarded for top finishers and best chasers. About the Come Out and Play Festival The annual Come Out and Play Festival seeks to provide a forum for new types of public games and play. Its mission is to gather designers of innovative new games and experiences, and bring those experiences to a public eager to rediscover the world around them. Started in New York City in 2006, 2013 is its fourth year in San Francisco. Journey to the End of the Night is part of Come Out and Play. Come for games on Saturday during the day, then stay for Journey! Saturday, November 9th-Sunday, November 10th http://comeoutandplaysf.org https://www.facebook.com/events/703899752973250/
Saturday, November 9, 2013 at 6:00pm in PST
Everett Middle School

The Digital Marketing Conference That Explores the New Nature of Influence: Hub Convene
Dustin Moskovitz was invited
The program kicks off with a keynote address from Brian Wong, the CEO of Kiip speaking on the power of mobile moments. Kiip has been named one of the world¹s 50 Most Innovative Companies by Fast Company, listed by Forbes as one of the 4 Hot Online Ad Companies to Put on Your Watch List and included on the Dow Jones FasTech50 List. After skipping four K-12 grades, Brian received his Bachelor of Commerce from the University of British Columbia at age 18, and shortly after became one of the youngest people to ever receive venture capital funding. The Hub, is a sister publication to PRWeek and the web’s premier resource for digital marketing news, tips and tools. Hub Convene is its first day-long conference, and it will explore the new nature of digital influence and engagement. From PR pros, to online marketers, this event is the first stop on the way to becoming a digital maven. In partnership with LinkedIn, the event will be held at The W Hotel in San Francisco on Monday, March 31 2014.
